\begin{abstract}
This is a project progress report for the term project for CSCI 562: Formal Specifications. This is the second of such reports and will detail the informal specifications agreed upon. An updated class diagram for the TCAS-II system will be an ongoing process. It is known that in today's U.S. Airspace, FAA rules have changed more rapidly than ever. As a quick sidebar: the reason for this is three-fold - 1) more planes in the air, 2) safety in all aspects of flight (including weather RADAR, intentional landings in zero-zero, collision avoidance, Class-G Airspace shrinking into Controlled Airspace), and 3) technology (including affordability). That said, knowing that TCAS-II is used by the vast majority of flights, (in the U.S.) Fairly simple FAA Rules will be briefly mentioned in at least one section of this Progress Report 2.
\end{abstract}

\section{Updated Class Diagram}
Figure \ref{fig:1} shows the most recent class diagram for the TCAS-II system onboard an aircraft operated by the fictional ``JohnsonAir'' company. We specifically chose this name to distinguish between the aircraft under operation (i.e. the one in which the TCAS-II system under UML design, is installed) and other aircraft within the vicinity of this aircraft. There is more information later, regarding the requirements for TCAS-II mandates.

Some notes about this diagram:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Every \texttt{Aircraft} is uniquely identified by its transponder ident. This ident is a 4-digit code (using numbers 0-7) that can change. The code may change as per usage or requirements of ATC's codes. \texttt{JohnsonAircraft}, like most General Aviation (GA) aircraft also has a unique immutable tail number for the life of the aircraft. According to ATC terminology, "aircraft ident" refers to the transponder squawk code, and "tail number" refers to the large painted alphanumeric characters on the tail, and/or the side of the aircraft, e.g., "N480DG", which is a Citation 500 series plane. ATC can also hail the PIC by firstly broadcasting the aircraft identifier (a la "tailnumber") as seen on their RADAR - "Flight 1930 Heavy" which is a large cargo transport airplane, or "Air Force One" which is any president's \textit{in-flight} aircraft. The latter two are of course not painted anywhere on the aircraft, as this is what is shown on ATC's RADAR display. The latter two examples are surrogate tail numbers.
    \item Every \texttt{Aircraft} has a unique \texttt{Location} that identifies it, as well.
    \item While within range of detection of the TCAS-II system onboard the \texttt{JohnsonAircraft} airplane, other \texttt{Aircraft} are tracked by the TCAS-II system as \texttt{Target}s until an \texttt{Advisory} is issued based on whether they are within the time-to-collision of the \texttt{JohnsonAircraft} airplane®. An \texttt{Intruder} object replaces the \texttt{Target} once an \texttt{Advisory} is issued.
    \item One and only one \texttt{Advisory} can be active for a given \texttt{Intruder}.
    \item Each \texttt{Advisory} has an \texttt{AdvisoryType}, which is one of three values: \texttt{Traffic\_Advisory}, \texttt{Resolution\_Advisory}, or \texttt{Clear\_Of\_Conflict}.
    \item \texttt{Clear\_Of\_Conflict} is issued when one of the other \texttt{Advisory} objects is resolved, and lasts until the \texttt{Intruder} is replaced once more by a \texttt{Target}, at which point the \texttt{Advisory} is removed.\\

    \item \textit{ADS-B/out must be discussed here, it is required in Class-B, Class-C, Class-D, and Class-E airspace when that airspace extends down to the surface, (except in some rural areas, not below 2000 AGL).}  \textit{This rule also applies to Class-E airspace at and above 10,000 MSL} (feet Mean Sea Level). These rules are in place because the airspace is becoming so dense, so fast.\\

    \textit{TCAS-II is mandated for Part-91 (GA), Part-121 (scheduled flights), and Part-135 (on-demand) aircraft operations with more than ten passenger seats. TCAS-II requires a Mode-S transponders.}\\

    Class G (uncontrolled) airspace, where FAA restrictions are fairly limited and ADS-B/out is not required, is becoming increasingly rare. For this reason, it is assumed that most all \texttt{Aircraft} are equipped with ADS-B/out and thus transmit their GPS coordinates (latitude and longitude).\\

    \item   The \texttt{DataMonitor} is a singleton object that monitors the transponder data for potential collisions and creates one or more \texttt{Advisory} objects. Each individual \texttt{Advisory} object will be associated with exactly one \texttt{Intruder} object. There will exist only a single \texttt{DataMonitor} within the entire system and it will be either on (enabled) or off (disabled, likely overridden).

    \item TCAS-II requires Mode-S transponders, of course. If the transponder however, is of Mode-C, then the \texttt{DataMonitor} will be disabled and no \texttt{Advisory} objects will be issued. \textit{If however, the \texttt{JohnsonAircraft} is equipped with TCAS-II, as it is assumed to be, but an intruder is Mode-C equipped, \texttt{JohnsonAircraft}'s TCAS-II can only annunciate "traffic" "traffic" "traffic"}. Since the system under UML design is a TCAS-II system, we assume that the equipped transponder of a \texttt{JohnsonAircraft} is always Mode-S.

    \item TCAS-II does not provide lateral resolutions. Regarding vertical resolutions, the \texttt{targetVerticalSpeed} of an \texttt{Advisory} will be positive if the pilot is instructed to climb, negative if the pilot is instructed to descend, or annunciated "level off" if the pilot is instructed to level off. If the pilot is instructed to maintain vertical speed, the \texttt{targetVerticalSpeed} will be set to the same value as the \texttt{verticalSpeed} of the \texttt{Aircraft} at the hand of the pilot flying (PF).
    \item tau is the ``time to close'', or effective time to collision, in seconds, assuming both aircraft maintain
    current climb rate and speed.
\end{itemize}

