\subsection{Issues and Blockers}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Papyrus was tried as a UML tool, but the design interface was non-intuitive. We used PlantUML, with VS Code integrations, to design the UML diagrams.
    \item We would really like to be able to specify UML diagrams using some form of \LaTeX based rendering. In other words,
    rather than simply importing a pre-rendered PNG into our \LaTeX document as we currently do, we would like to
    specify the PlantUML in \LaTeX directly, and have it render as part of the rendering process inherent in document
    generation. We may have to switch away from PlantUML to another tool to get this to work.
    \item The tool being used to track the project is Monday, but our subscription trial has run out. We may look into using something else, such as Linear, Notion, or some other tool, to maintain the Gantt chart. Monday is relatively expensive, and somewhat overkill for this project. We could use some advice on another tool that the University has a subscription to.
    \item S. Johnson is on travel from Mar 21-Mar 30 and again from April 20-24. He should have access to email during the second of these trips, but during the first, internet access will be spotty at best.
    \item When originally designing the first specification, it was common for \texttt{fuzz} to report undefined
    identifiers in schemas that utilized other schemas (e.g. \texttt{Aircraft}, which uses \texttt{Location}), if the
    utilized schema was not declared before the utilizing schema. It took a bit to realize that the ordering of
    declarations in Z matters.
    \item When we added the numerical constraint for \texttt{Location}:
        \[ \text{latitude} \geq -90 \land \text{latitude} \leq 90 \]
        we encountered a type mismatch in \texttt{fuzz}. This occurs because the standard
        Z toolkit defines the $\geq$ and $\leq$ relations strictly for integers ($\mathbb{Z}$).
        Since \texttt{latitude} is defined as the given set \texttt{FLOAT}, the checker
        does not recognize the comparison.

        The error reported by \texttt{fuzz} is:
    \begin{verbatim}
    "specification-2.latex", line 27: Type mismatch
    > Predicate: latitude \geq -90
    > Arg type:  FLOAT
    > Expected:  ZZ
    \end{verbatim}

    To resolve this, we took a pragmatic approach by simply redefining our units. For example, latitude will be
    specified in millidegrees (instead of degrees), and this allows us to represent \texttt{FLOAT}(s) as integers.

\end{itemize}

